example.p:
Solution: We know that the answer is \frac\pi4, but we can also compute this as an  integral  we saw this way back in Example:


  \text{area} &= \int_0^1 \sqrt{1-x^2} \dee{x}





	To simplify the integrand we substitute x=\sin u. With this choice  \diff{x}{u}=\cos u and so \dee{x}=\cos u \dee{u}.



	We also need to translate the limits of integration and it is perhaps  easiest to do this by writing u as a function of x  namely u(x)=\arcsin  x. Hence u(0)=0 and u(1)=\frac{\pi}{2}.



	Hence the integral becomes


	  \int_0^1 \sqrt{1-x^2}\dee{x}
	&= \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \sqrt{1-\sin^2u} \cdot \cos u \dee{u}

	&= \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \sqrt{\cos^2u} \cdot \cos u \dee{u}

	&= \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \cos^2 u \dee{u}


	Notice that here we have used that the positive square root \sqrt{\cos^2  u} = |\cos u|=\cos u because  \cos(u)\geq 0 for 0 \leq u \leq  \frac\pi2.



	To go further we use the techniques of Section.


	\int_0^1 \sqrt{1-x^2}\dee{x}
	&= \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}}\cos^2 u \dee{u} \qquad\qquad \text{and since $\cos^2u=\frac{1+\cos2u}{2}$}

	&= \frac{1}{2}\int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} (1+\cos(2 u)) \dee{u}

	&= \frac{1}{2} \bigg[u + \frac{1}{2}\sin(2u) \bigg]_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}}

	&= \frac{1}{2} \left(\frac{\pi}{2}-0 + \frac{\sin\pi}{2}-\frac{\sin 0}{2} \right)

	&= \frac{\pi}{4}\checkmark

Solution: We proceed much as we did in the previous example.



	To simplify the integrand we substitute x=\sin u. With this choice  \diff{x}{u}=\cos u and so \dee{x}=\cos u \dee{u}. Also note that u=\arcsin x.



	The integral becomes


	 \int \frac{x^2}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dee{x}
	&= \int \frac{\sin^2u}{\sqrt{1-\sin^2u}} \cdot \cos u \dee{u}

	&= \int \frac{\sin^2u}{\sqrt{\cos^2u}} \cdot \cos u \dee{u}





	To proceed further we need to get rid of the square-root. Since u=\arcsin x has  domain -1\leq x \leq 1 and range -\frac\pi2 \leq u \leq \frac\pi2, it follows  that \cos u \geq 0 (since cosine is non-negative on these inputs). Hence


	\sqrt{\cos^2u} &= \cos u & \text{when $-\frac\pi2 \leq u \leq \frac\pi2 $}





	So our integral now becomes


	 \int \frac{x^2}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dee{x}
	&= \int \frac{\sin^2u}{\sqrt{\cos^2u}} \cdot \cos u \dee{u}

	&= \int \frac{\sin^2u}{\cos u} \cdot \cos u \dee{u}

	&= \int \sin^2u \dee{u}

	&= \frac{1}{2} \int (1-\cos 2u) \dee{u} \qquad
	\text{by Equation }

	&= \frac{u}{2} - \frac{1}{4}\sin 2u +C

	&= \frac{1}{2}\arcsin x - \frac{1}{4} \sin(2\arcsin x) +C





	We can simplify this further using a double-angle identity. Recall that u =  \arcsin  x and that x=\sin u. Then


	\sin 2u &= 2 \sin u \cos u



		We can replace \cos u using \cos^2u = 1 - \sin^2u. Taking a  square-root of this formula gives \cos u= \pm \sqrt{1-\sin^2u}. We need the  positive branch here since \cos u \geq 0 when -\frac\pi2 \leq u  \leq \frac\pi2 (which is exactly the range of \arcsin x). Continuing along:


	  \sin2u
	  &= 2 \sin u \cdot \sqrt{1-\sin^2 u}

	  &= 2 x \sqrt{1-x^2}


	Thus our solution is


	\int \frac{x^2}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dee{x}
	&= \frac{1}{2}\arcsin x - \frac{1}{4} \sin(2\arcsin x) +C

	&= \frac{1}{2}\arcsin x - \frac{1}{2} x \sqrt{1-x^2} +C

We'll set up the integral using vertical strips. The strip in the figure has width \dee{x} and height \sqrt{r^2-x^2}. So the area is given by the integral


\text{area} &= \int_a^r \sqrt{r^2-x^2}\dee{x}


Which is very similar to the previous example.

ul.li:
To evaluate the integral we substitute


x&=x(u)=r\sin u & \dee{x} &= \diff{x}{u} \dee{u}  =r\cos u\dee{u}


It is also helpful to write u as a function of x  namely u  =\arcsin\frac{x}{r}.

The integral runs from x=a to x=r. These correspond to


  u(r) &= \arcsin \frac{r}{r} = \arcsin 1 = \frac{\pi}{2}

  u(a) &= \arcsin \frac{a}{r} \quad \text{ which does not simplify further}

The integral then becomes


  \int_a^r \sqrt{r^2-x^2} \dee{x}
&= \int_{\arcsin(a/r)}^{\frac\pi2} \sqrt{r^2-r^2\sin^2u} \cdot r \cos u \dee{u}

&= \int_{\arcsin(a/r)}^{\frac\pi2} r^2 \sqrt{1-\sin^2u} \cdot \cos u \dee{u}

&= r^2\int_{\arcsin(a/r)}^{\frac\pi2} \sqrt{\cos^2u} \cdot \cos u \dee{u}


To proceed further (as we did in Examples and)  we
need to think about whether \cos u is positive or negative.

Putting this fact into our integral we get


\int_a^r \sqrt{r^2-x^2} \dee{x}
&= r^2\int_{\arcsin(a/r)}^{\frac\pi2} \sqrt{\cos^2u} \cdot \cos u \dee{u}

&= r^2 \int_{\arcsin(a/r)}^{\frac\pi2} \cos^2 u \dee{u}


	Recall the identity \cos^2u=\frac{1+\cos2u}{2} from Section


&= \frac{r^2}{2} \int_{\arcsin(a/r)}^{\frac\pi2} (1 +\cos 2u) \dee{u}

&= \frac{r^2}{2} \bigg[u + \frac{1}{2}\sin(2u) \bigg]_{\arcsin(a/r)}^{\frac\pi2}

&= \frac{r^2}{2} \left(\frac{\pi}{2} +\frac{1}{2}\sin\pi - \arcsin(a/r) -
\frac{1}{2}\sin( 2\arcsin(a/r)) \right)

&= \frac{r^2}{2} \left(\frac{\pi}{2} - \arcsin(a/r) - \frac{1}{2}\sin( 2\arcsin(a/r))
\right)


Oof! But there is a little further to go before we are done.

So finally the area is


\text{area} &= \int_a^r \sqrt{r^2-x^2} \dee{x}

&= \frac{r^2}{2} \left(\frac{\pi}{2} - \arcsin(a/r) - \frac{1}{2}\sin( 2\arcsin(a/r))
\right)

&= \frac{\pi r^2}{4} - \frac{r^2}{2} \arcsin(a/r) - \frac{a}{2} \sqrt{r^2-a^2}

example.p:
Solution: This integral is much more easily evaluated using the simple substitution u=r^2-x^2.



	Set u=r^2-x^2. Then \dee{u}=-2x\dee{x}, and so


	\int_a^r x\sqrt{r^2-x^2}\dee{x} &=\int_{r^2-a^2}^0 \sqrt{u}\ \frac{\dee{u}}{-2}

	&=-\frac{1}{2}\bigg[\frac{u^{3/2}}{3/2}\bigg]_{r^2-a^2}^0

	&=\frac{1}{3}\big[r^2-a^2\big]^{3/2}

Solution: As per our guidelines at the start of this section, the presence of the square root  term \sqrt{3^2+x^2} tells us to substitute x=3\tan u.



	Substitute


	x&=3\tan u &
	\dee{x} &= 3\sec^2 u\dee{u}


	This allows us to remove the square root:


	\sqrt{9+x^2}
	&=\sqrt{9+9\tan^2u}
	=3\sqrt{1+\tan^2u}
	=3\sqrt{\sec^2 u}
	=3|\sec u|





	Hence our integral becomes


	 \int \frac{\dee{x}}{x^2\sqrt{9+x^2}}
	  &= \int \frac{3\sec^2 u}{9\tan^2u \cdot 3|\sec u|} \dee{u}





	To remove the absolute value we must consider the range of values of u in  the integral. Since x=3\tan u we have u = \arctan(x/3). The range

		To be  pedantic, we mean the range of the standard arctangent function or its principal  value. One can define other arctangent functions with different ranges.

	of arctangent  is -\frac{\pi}{2} \leq \arctan  \leq \frac{\pi}{2} and so u=\arctan(x/3)  will always like between -\frac{\pi}{2} and +\frac{\pi}{2}. Hence \cos u  will always be positive, which in turn implies that |\sec u|=\sec u.



	Using this fact our integral becomes:


	 \int \frac{\dee{x}}{x^2\sqrt{9+x^2}}
	  &= \int \frac{3\sec^2 u}{27 \tan^2u |\sec u|} \dee{u}

	  &= \frac{1}{9}\int \frac{\sec u}{\tan^2u} \dee{u} & \text{since $\sec u  \gt  0$}





	Rewrite this in terms of sine and cosine


	\int \frac{\dee{x}}{x^2\sqrt{9+x^2}}
	&= \frac{1}{9}\int \frac{\sec u}{\tan^2u} \dee{u}\\
	&= \frac{1}{9} \int \frac{1}{\cos u}\cdot \frac{\cos^2u}{\sin^2 u}\dee{u}
	= \frac{1}{9} \int \frac{\cos u}{\sin^2 u}\dee{u}


		Now we can use the substitution rule with y=\sin u and \dee{y}=\cos u\dee{u}


	&= \frac{1}{9} \int \frac{\dee{y}}{y^2} \\
	&= -\frac{1}{9y} +C \\
	&= -\frac{1}{9\sin u}+C







	The original integral was a function of x, so we still have to rewrite \sin u in terms of x. Remember that x=3 \tan u or  u=\arctan(x/3). So u is the angle shown in the triangle below and we can read off the triangle that


	\sin u &= \frac{x}{\sqrt{9+x^2}}


	\implies \int\frac{\dee{x}}{x^2\sqrt{9+x^2}} &= -\frac{\sqrt{9+x^2}}{9x}  +C

Solution: This one requires a secant substitution, but otherwise is very similar to those
above.



	Set x = \sec u and \dee{x}=\sec u \tan u \dee{u}. Then


	  \int \frac{x^2}{\sqrt{x^2-1}} \dee{x}
	&= \int \frac{\sec^2 u}{\sqrt{\sec^2u-1}} \sec u \tan u \dee{u}

	&= \int \sec^3 u \cdot \frac{ \tan u}{\sqrt{\tan^2u}}  \dee{u}
	\qquad \text{since $\tan^2u = \sec^2u-1$}

	&= \int \sec^3u \cdot \frac{\tan u}{|\tan u|} \dee{u}







	As before we need to consider the range of u values in order to determine the  sign of \tan u. Notice that the integrand is only defined when either x \lt -1 or x \gt 1;  thus we should treat the cases x \lt -1 and x \gt 1 separately. Let us assume that x \gt 1 and  we will come back to the case x \lt -1 at the end of the example.




	When x \gt 1, our u=\arcsec x takes values in (0,\frac\pi2). This follows  since when 0 \lt u \lt \frac\pi2, we have 0 \lt \cos u \lt 1 and so \sec u \gt 1. Further, when  0 \lt u \lt \frac\pi2, we have \tan u \gt 0. Thus |\tan u|=\tan u.




	Back to our integral, when x> 1:


	  \int \frac{x^2}{\sqrt{x^2-1}} \dee{x}
	&= \int \sec^3u \cdot \frac{\tan u}{|\tan u|} \dee{u}

	&= \int \sec^3u \dee{u} & \text{since } \tan u\geq 0


		This is exactly Example 


	&= \frac{1}{2}\sec u \tan u + \frac{1}{2} \log| \sec u + \tan u| +C





	Since we started with a function of x we need to finish with one. We know that  \sec u = x and then we can use trig identities


	  \tan^2 u &= \sec^2 u - 1 = x^2-1 & \text{so }
	  \tan u &= \pm \sqrt{x^2-1}


	but we know


	\tan u & \geq 0 & \text{so }
	  \tan u &= \sqrt{x^2-1}


	Thus


	\int \frac{x^2}{\sqrt{x^2-1}} \dee{x}
	&= \frac{1}{2}x\sqrt{x^2-1} + \frac{1}{2}\log| x +\sqrt{x^2-1}| +C





	The above holds when x \gt 1. We can confirm that it is also true when x \lt -1 by  showing the right-hand side is a valid antiderivative of the integrand. To do so we must  differentiate our answer. Notice that we do not need to consider the sign of  x+\sqrt{x^2-1} when we differentiate since we have already seen that


	  \diff{}{x} \log|x| &= \frac{1}{x}


	when either x \lt 0 or x \gt 0. So the following computation applies to both x \gt 1 and  x \lt -1. The expressions become quite long so we differentiate each term  separately:


	\diff{}{x} \left[ x\sqrt{x^2-1} \right]
	&=\left[ \sqrt{x^2-1} +  \frac{x^2}{\sqrt{x^2-1}} \right]

	&= \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-1}} \left[(x^2-1) + x^2 \right]

	\diff{}{x} \log\bigg| x +\sqrt{x^2-1} \bigg|
	&= \frac{1}{x+\sqrt{x^2-1}} \cdot \left[ 1+\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2-1}} \right]

	&= \frac{1}{x+\sqrt{x^2-1}} \cdot \frac{x+\sqrt{x^2-1}}{\sqrt{x^2-1}}

	&= \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-1}}


	Putting things together then gives us


	& \diff{}{x} \left[ \frac{1}{2}x\sqrt{x^2-1} + \frac{1}{2}\log| x +\sqrt{x^2-1}| +C  \right]


	&= \frac{1}{2\sqrt{x^2-1}} \left[(x^2-1) + x^2 + 1 \right]+0

	&= \frac{x^2}{\sqrt{x^2-1}}


	This tells us that our answer for x \gt 1 is also valid when x \lt -1 and so


	\int \frac{x^2}{\sqrt{x^2-1}} \dee{x} &= \frac{1}{2}x\sqrt{x^2-1} + \frac{1}{2}\log| x +\sqrt{x^2-1}| +C


	when x \lt -1 and when x \gt 1.

ul.li:
Once this is done we can convert the square root of the integrand into a standard  form by making the simple substitution y=x-1. Here goes


& \int_3^5\frac{\sqrt{x^2-2x-3}}{x-1}\dee{x}


&=\int_3^5\frac{\sqrt{(x-1)^2-4}}{x-1}\dee{x}

&=\int_2^4\frac{\sqrt{y^2-4}}{y}\dee{y}
&\text{with } y=x-1, \dee{y} = \dee{x}

&=\int_0^{\pi/3}\frac{\sqrt{4\sec^2u-4}}{2\sec u}\ 2\sec u\tan u\dee{u}
&\text{with } y=2\sec u

&& \text{and }\dee{y} = 2\sec u\tan u\dee{u}


Notice that we could also do this in fewer steps by setting (x-1)=2\sec u,  \dee{x}=2\sec u\tan u\dee{u}.

Now returning to the evaluation of the integral, we simplify and continue.


\int_3^5\frac{\sqrt{x^2-2x-3}}{x-1}\dee{x}
&=\int_0^{\pi/3} 2\sqrt{\sec^2 u -1}\ \tan u\dee{u}

&=2\int_0^{\pi/3} \tan^2 u\dee{u}
\qquad\text{since } \sec^2u=1+\tan^2u


	In taking the square root of \sec^2u-1=\tan^2u we used that \tan u\ge 0 on  the range 0\le u\le \frac{\pi}{3}.


&=2\int_0^{\pi/3}\big[ \sec^2 u-1\big]\dee{u}
\qquad\quad\text{since $\sec^2u=1+\tan^2u$, again}

&=2\Big[\tan u - u\Big]_0^{\pi/3}

&=2\big[\sqrt{3}-\frac{\pi}{3}\big]
